      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nthe good news is: we do not create empty xattr even via nfs just like I thought, ext4 handles it for us:\n\n[root@oleg95-server tests]# mount localhost:/mnt/lustre /mnt/nfs -t nfs\n[root@oleg95-server tests]# touch /tmp/testfile\n[root@oleg95-server tests]# chmod 644 /tmp/testfile \n[root@oleg95-server tests]# cp -p /tmp/testfile /mnt/nfs/  \n[root@oleg95-server tests]# stat -c %a /mnt/nfs/testfile \n644\n[root@oleg95-server tests]# getfattr -d -m system.posix_acl_access -e hex /mnt/nfs/testfile \n[root@oleg95-server tests]# getfattr -d -m system.posix_acl_access -e hex /mnt/lustre/testfile \n[root@oleg95-server tests]#\n\nUnfortunately error code is 0 so we cannot use that to determine if the attribute is there or not though.. Should we just wc -l the output or some such?\n\n[root@oleg95-server tests]# getfattr -d -m system.posix_acl_access -e hex /mnt/nfs/testfile   \n[root@oleg95-server tests]# echo $?\n0",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
